{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/tailor-figures-for-papers-and-presentations-63cd37228312", "time": 1683009548.04828, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/tailor-figures-for-papers-and-presentations-63cd37228312/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Modify Figures for Papers and Presentations | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Easily Tailor Figures for Papers and Presentations", "description": "What works for screens doesn't work for slides. Learn how to easily tailor figures to different mediums using matplotlib. Don't make your audience squint."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.osha.gov/SLTC/etools/computerworkstations/components_monitors.html", "anchor_text": "1 foot screen from 2.5 feet away", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.projectorscreen.com/projector-screen-calculators", "anchor_text": "10 feet screen from 40 feet away", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://matplotlib.org/3.2.1/tutorials/introductory/customizing.html", "anchor_text": "Style sheets", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html", "anchor_text": "several pre-made style sheets", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/Rcssplot/vignettes/Rcssplot.pdf", "anchor_text": "cascading style sheets package", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://dgleich.wordpress.com/2013/06/04/creating-high-quality-graphics-in-matlab-for-papers-and-presentations/", "anchor_text": "this blog", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://pypi.org/project/plotsettings/", "anchor_text": "plotsettings", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1003833", "anchor_text": "PLOS article", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "http://krishnakrao.github.io", "anchor_text": "krishnakrao.github.io", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["Have you ever sat in a presentation and squinted at the slides struggling to read charts with tiny text? Or worse, encountered a blurry figure in a poster making it impossible to read the axes? Too often people tend to reproduce the same figure across different mediums like articles on website, presentation slides, journal articles (pdf documents), leading to unpleasant user experience. Let\u2019s be better.", "In this article, you will learn-", "The examples I share are written in python but I provide resources to replicate the same approach in R and Matlab.", "The most common mistake people make while preparing a presentation is to use the same figure that they used in their online/journal article. This is wrong because people view articles and presentations from different perceived distances. While one reads an article on an approximately 1 foot screen from 2.5 feet away, they view presentations on approximately 10 feet screen from 40 feet away.", "This means that a figure which looks readable on a computer screen may not be readable when projected on a slide and viewed from the last row of a room. Thus, figure elements must be enlarged. As a rule of thumb, if you are making a chart/figure on your laptop but would like to include it in a presentation, take one step backward and check if the figure is readable. If not, enlarge annotations and thicken the lines/points and try again.", "However, doing this manually for each figure, or each time you wish to convert your figures is tedious. How can we automate this?", "Style sheets are an easy way to source several styling commands automatically. Essentially, they contain instructions to alter the default style parameters for different elements like figure size, line width, etc. Even though matplotlib comes with several pre-made style sheets, most of them are focused on aesthetics and not on plotting mediums.", "To create your own style sheets for different mediums:", "If you are an R user, you can follow along this article using cascading style sheets package. If you are a Matlab user (my sympathies), you can create custom .m files as style sheets using the commands mentioned at the end of this blog. With that, let\u2019s learn what style parameters to use for different mediums.", "Most of our figure-making practices are already tailored towards articles and papers since we view them at the same distance as we created them. So whatever looks good when you create a figure should suffice while publishing it.", "I use the following style sheet to create figures for my online articles (contents of my \u201carticle.mplstyle\u201d file):", "For journal papers, I stay away from tweaking styles by myself due to many journal-to-journal differences. Instead, I use plotsettings which is a python package built exactly for that- automatically tailoring figures based on each journal\u2019s rules.", "For presentations, I thicken line elements, enlarge marker elements, ramp up the resolution and blow-up the text-elements by 1.5 times. This is roughly proportional to the viewing ratios (4/2.5 ~ 1.5) and ensures that the figures I create on my laptop look the same on a projector when viewed from the last row. I use the following style sheet to create figures for my presentations (contents of my \u201cpresentation.mplstyle\u201d file):", "The difference is easily noticeable on comparing the outputs produced from the two style sheets:", "Finally, apart from resizing, there are many other tweaks that help make your figures more readable in a presentation. You could reduce the amount of data presented, use colors that will render easily on a projector, etc. Such tips can be found in this excellent PLOS article.", "Have other ways to tailor figures to different mediums? Leave a response below.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Earth Scientist & Bicycle Traveler | krishnakrao.github.io"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F63cd37228312&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnde